varkarrus0: @kyeotic I think the caching part could already could be done (it was mentioned in this PR); basically, some serverless adapters (say Cloudflare Workers) allow caching if you set the `cf` object in the `RequestInit` object with some options when using the JS `fetch`, see here: https://developers.cloudflare.com/workers/examples/cache-using-fetch/

I modified the example code a bit here to match what I am actually using:
```js
$router.use("/api/*",
    jwk({
        jwks_uri: (c) => c.env.AUTH_ORIGIN + "/.well-known/jwks.json",
        allow_anon: true
    }, {
        cf: { cacheTtl: 3600, cacheEverything: true }
    })
);
```
This will cache the `jwks.json` for the datacenter the cloudflare worker was called in for 1 hour as far as I know.

If you're not using Cloudflare Workers but another serverless platform, say Vercel, I think they also have their own options too such as `cache` property (instead of `cf`). If no caching options are available for your adapter (cause the platform doesn't support them), some serverless platforms might respect the caching headers you send in `fetch` anyways, so you could try setting some options in `headers` instead; check the docs of the serverless platform you use on caching.

If you're not using a serverless platform (but your own server), then most likely your headers would be respected! You just need to configure your server if it doesn't. But if all fails (somehow), you could also implement your own custom caching using the `keys` param (as a last resort) in the jwk middleware which I find very flexible; simply write your entire caching logic there and return the keys at the end, but again, this is a last resort.

kyeotic: I would be happy with a simple in-memory cache by default.

buckett: @varkarrus0 With something like:

> ```js
>         cf: { cacheTtl: 3600, cacheEverything: true }
> );
> ```

Just watch out caching everything means if the remote server ever has a blip and returns a 500 temporarily you'll end up caching that for as hour as well (even if it recovers quickly). Adjusting the cache timeout depending on the HTTP status allows good caching but also good recovery in the event of a problem on the remote server. For example:
```js
            cf: { cacheTtlByStatus: { "200-299": 86400, "404": 1, "500-599": 0 } }
```

