usualoma: @yusukebe Improved CSS helper by fd2ea73 and 5f0ba8b
How about this?

## Changes


### Pseudo selectors

There's both good news and bad news.

* Bad News: The selector for pseudo-elements using '&' has been removed due to its overly complex implementation.
* Good News: Pseudo-elements using '&' are now almost universally supported by browsers.
    * [caniuse.com/css-nesting](https://caniuse.com/css-nesting)

I believe that we should start with a small release as an MVP (Minimum Viable Product) to evaluate its value. Therefore, if it works in the latest browsers, it would be a wise choice to consider it not supported here.


### `createCssContext()`

Default `css` and `Style` are also provided, but you can create your own using `createCssContext()` if you want to use them in a context separate from this one.

The test code will show you how to use it.
https://github.com/honojs/hono/pull/1858/files#diff-b13e9a99ad47b9364486431c602062116158762edc7a647fa557b8c80a76774cR181-R203

### escape variable

Variables embedded in `${}` are now escaped. This is the same as html`<h1>${'(><;) crying...</h1>` being escaped, which is a satisfactory specification in the hono. However, I feel a little uneasy about the difference from there, since it seems that styled-components does not escape.

```ts
css`
    animation: 1s ${animation} ease-in-out;
    background-color: green;
    color: white;
    padding: 1rem;
    transition: opacity 0.1s ease-in-out;

    &::after {
      margin-left: 1rem;
      content: "${`I'm a hono!`}"; // will be escaped
    }

    &:hover {
      opacity: 0.5;
    }
  `
```


### Embed sub `css`

This was added in the last e4ceb1e. This feature allows a very large possibility to generate CSS programmatically.
Nevertheless, it may be overkill. I think we can revert this commit if it is not needed.

```ts
const FizzBuzz = () => {
  const list = [...Array(20)].map((_, i) => i + 1)
  const className = css`
    ${list.map((n) => {
      const fizz = n % 3 === 0
      const buzz = n % 5 === 0
      return css`
        :nth-child(${n}):after {
          margin-left: 1rem;
          content: '${fizz && buzz ? 'FizzBuzz' : fizz ? 'Fizz' : buzz ? 'Buzz' : ''}';
        }
      `
    })}
  `

  return (
    <ul class={className}>
      {list.map((n) => (
        <li>{n}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  )
}

app.get('/', (c) => {
  return c.render(<FizzBuzz />)
})
```

